      Robinhood After Dark
   =20
 =20
Historically there were people whose job it was to trade stocks, and they s=
howed up at the New York Stock Exchange building each weekday from 9:30 to =
4 to trade stocks, and if you wanted to trade stocks your best bet was to s=
how up there and trade with them. Now those people are mostly for decoratio=
n, and the stocks trade on computers. But there are still people whose job =
it is to trade stocks, or at least to supervise the computers,=C2=A0and a l=
ot of them work in New York, and it would be inhumane to expect them to tra=
de stocks 24 hours a day, seven days a week.So the U.S. stock exchanges sti=
ll keep those traditional opening hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. New York tim=
e, and most of the people and computers=C2=A0whose job it is to trade stock=
s trade stocks mostly during those hours. Not entirely; the exchanges have =
extended hours in the morning and evening, and I suppose technically you co=
uld meet someone at a bar at midnight and agree to sell her some stock.[1] =
But most of the trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the trading that =E2=80=9Ccounts=
,=E2=80=9D that sets official prices and so forth =E2=80=94 is during the r=
egular hours.=C2=A0And in fact it would mostly be counterproductive for the=
 people whose job it is to trade stocks to trade stocks for longer hours. W=
hen your job is to trade stocks, you want to trade stocks when everyone els=
e trades stocks. There are advantages to concentrating liquidity; if everyo=
ne does all of their trading in the same half-hour window there will be mor=
e people to trade with during that window than if everyone=E2=80=99s tradin=
g is spaced out over 7 hours. (Plus:  You=E2=80=99d have more free time.) A=
nd in fact liquidity in U.S. stock markets=C2=A0is=C2=A0increasingly concen=
trated in one half-hour window, the 30 minutes before the markets close at =
4 p.m. All the people whose job it is to trade stocks know that all the oth=
er people whose job it is to trade stocks show up between 3:30 and 4, so th=
at=E2=80=99s when they show up too.But there are other people whose job is =
not to trade stocks. There are people whose jobs are to be dentists, or  fi=
nancial wellness educators, or college administrators or pool salespeople o=
r IT consultants. Many of these people also like to trade stocks, not as a =
job, but for fun and also maybe profit who knows. But they show up to work =
at 9 and leave at 5 and spend the time in between doing their jobs, which p=
revent=C2=A0them from devoting the time they=E2=80=99d like to trading stoc=
ks. Then they leave work and commute home and have dinner and put the kids =
to bed and pour themselves a nice Scotch and sit down to trade stocks but, =
whoops, the market has been closed for hours.=C2=A0These people are the cor=
e customers of Robinhood Markets Inc., which caters to them=C2=A0mainly=C2=
=A0by having an easy-to-use smartphone app that allows them to trade stocks=
 quickly during the day when they=E2=80=99re supposed to be doing their job=
s. But,  now, also:Robinhood Markets Inc. shares jumped as much as 28% afte=
r announcing plans to extend the trading day for customers by four hours.Tr=
ading will run from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. New York time, a step toward offering =
24-hour equities investing, the Menlo Park, California-based company said i=
n a blog post Tuesday.The shares rose the most since August on the news and=
 were up 24% to $15.85 at 11:22 a.m. in New York.=C2=A0=E2=80=9COur custome=
rs often tell us they=E2=80=99re working or preoccupied during regular mark=
et hours, limiting their ability to invest on their own schedule or evaluat=
e and react to important market news,=E2=80=9D Robinhood said in the blog p=
ost.Traditional market hours run from 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. and Robinhood alr=
eady offered extended trading starting at 9 a.m. and ending at 6 p.m. There=
=E2=80=99s reason for Robinhood=E2=80=99s 22.7 million customers to be wary=
 of the change, however. Extended-hours trading come with risk, including l=
ower liquidity (or opportunities to buy and sell) and the potential for hig=
her volatility, which could lead to customers getting a worse price than in=
 market hours.=C2=A0Well but =E2=80=9Clower liquidity=E2=80=9D just means =
=E2=80=9Cnobody trades then,=E2=80=9D and nobody trades then because Robinh=
ood hasn=E2=80=99t let them yet. Robinhood can create its own liquidity! Yo=
u just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0you know, you have one deep liquid trading session fr=
om 3:30 to 4 p.m. for the index funds and other professionals to trade with=
 each other and set a closing price, and you have another deep liquid tradi=
ng session from 7:30 to 8 p.m. for all the dentists and Redditors to trade =
with each other and have fun, and the other 12 or 23 hours are a ghost town=
. It=E2=80=99s fine. Last call at the Robinhood saloon will be liquid, if p=
eople want it to be. Eventually stocks will report two closing prices per d=
ay, the 4 p.m. close on the stock exchange and the 8 p.m. close on Robinhoo=
d.Actually, the blog post says that =E2=80=9CRobinhood is working towards o=
ffering 24/7 investing,=E2=80=9D and if that works out I suppose that the r=
eal Robinhood action will be even later at night, once the Scotch really ki=
cks in. (To be fair, presumably this will also be aimed at non-U.S. investo=
rs trading U.S. stocks during their daylight hours.)Robinhood=E2=80=99s sto=
ck closed up 24.2% yesterday on this news. There is something a bit odd abo=
ut that. =E2=80=9CTD Ameritrade is letting retail investors trade 24 hours =
a day, five days a week, and the brand has enlisted Lionel Richie to help t=
ell the story,=E2=80=9D it says here, in an article from 2018 about a=C2=A0=
Super Bowl ad=C2=A0for TD Ameritrade=E2=80=99s all-night trading session. (=
Here=E2=80=99s the ad.)=C2=A0That is limited to=C2=A0exchange-traded funds,=
 though, not single stocks. But the 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. trading day for U.S. s=
tocks seems pretty standard at retail brokerages including TD Ameritrade, E=
*Trade,=C2=A0Fidelity, Charles Schwab=C2=A0and=C2=A0Interactive Brokers. Ro=
binhood offered shorter=C2=A0trading hours than its competitors, and now it=
 is catching up, and its stock is up 24%.I suppose one way to read the pric=
e move is that the market thinks that Robinhood, unlike its competitors, is=
 really good at=C2=A0influencing its customers=E2=80=99 behavior, and at ge=
tting them to trade more.[2] TD Ameritrade hires Lionel Richie to pitch all=
-night stock trading during the Super Bowl, and its customers shrug and con=
tinue trading on their lunch breaks. Robinhood puts out a blog post about a=
fter-hours trading, and its customers say =E2=80=9Cwell now I know what I=
=E2=80=99m=C2=A0doing between 6 and 8 every evening!=E2=80=9D Other brokers=
 try to satisfy customer demand for extended trading, even if there isn=E2=
=80=99t very much of it; Robinhood creates its own demand.One more point ab=
out the extended session: The way this will work is not exactly that the de=
ntists will trade stocks back and forth with each other at 7 p.m. The way t=
his works is  the way that Robinhood trading works anyway: Its customers wi=
ll put in orders, and Robinhood will route those orders to a handful of big=
 market makers (Virtu Financial Inc., Citadel Securities LLC, G1X Execution=
 Services LLC, Two Sigma Securities LLC, etc.), and those market makers wil=
l fill those orders from their own inventory or execute them on an exchange=
 or dark pool. In general, during the day, the market makers will fill the =
orders at a price that is at least as good as the =E2=80=9Cnational best bi=
d and offer=E2=80=9D: If you=E2=80=99re buying stock, the market maker will=
 sell it to you at either the lowest available price on a public stock exch=
ange, or a slightly lower price. They do this in part because of Robinhood=
=E2=80=99s legal obligation to give you =E2=80=9Cbest execution=E2=80=9D on=
 your trades, but also because of a thicket of other rules (called =E2=80=
=9CRegulation NMS=E2=80=9D) regulating the routing of orders and the priori=
ty of the best=C2=A0price.After hours, when the exchanges are closed, or cl=
osed-ish, all of this is a bit more relaxed. There are still best execution=
 requirements, but the Reg NMS rules about the national best bid and offer =
apply only during =E2=80=9Cregular trading hours.=E2=80=9D[3] There are few=
er public quotes on public stock exchanges, and fewer traders and market ma=
kers quoting the stock; market makers will have to build their models of wh=
at the right price is based on more limited data. During the regular tradin=
g day, there are very visible prices and fierce competition to make those p=
rices as tight and accurate as possible. At night, who knows! Spreads will =
presumably be wider,[4]=C2=A0and people who  complain about Robinhood selli=
ng its orders to market makers will have more to complain about.
