   =20
      Volcano bonds
   =20
 =20
Maybe the one trade I have ever suggested in this column (still not financi=
al advice!)  was:=09Don=E2=80=99t buy El Salvador=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cvolcan=
o bond,=E2=80=9D a 6.5% 10-year dollar bond that also includes a call optio=
n on Bitcoins.=09Instead, buy El Salvador=E2=80=99s regular 8.25% dollar bo=
nd due in 2032 at like 75 cents on the dollar, and use the extra 25 cents t=
o buy Bitcoin.I mean, I=E2=80=99m not saying you should do the second trade=
 either, really. I=E2=80=99m just saying that if you find the volcano bond =
tempting, buying something that is worth more in every scenario=C2=A0should=
 be=C2=A0more=C2=A0tempting.Since I wrote that, the 8.25% bonds have traded=
 down to around 50 cents on the dollar, for a yield of about 20%. Oops? Mea=
nwhile the volcano bonds have not priced yet, but they continue to lurch al=
ong, apparently on the previously advertised terms. This makes them a much,=
 much worse deal. But they were always a bad deal, so it=E2=80=99s not clea=
r why that would matter. Anyway here=E2=80=99s some more on the volcano bon=
ds, from the Financial Times:El Salvador=E2=80=99s $1bn bitcoin-backed bond=
 could tap deep wells of capital among cryptocurrency enthusiasts after man=
y big international investors have shunned the project.Demand from bitcoin =
=E2=80=9Cwhales=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 investors holding large quantities of th=
e world=E2=80=99s biggest cryptocurrency =E2=80=94 is likely to be crucial =
to fundraising for the bond, according to people involved with the effort. =
...The optimism in the crypto community for the offering, which is the firs=
t of its kind from a sovereign borrower, sharply contrasts with most large =
traditional investors, who have said they are highly sceptical of the deal.=
Buyers of the 10-year bitcoin bond =E2=80=94 which offers an annual interes=
t rate of 6.5 per cent along with a share of any upside from the proceeds i=
nvested in bitcoin =E2=80=94 would be offering financing on favourable term=
s to El Salvador, whose existing 10-year dollar bonds currently yield in ex=
cess of 20 per cent.After a five-year lock-up period El Salvador will sell =
bitcoin until it recoups its initial investment and then share half of any =
profit with investors.Those yields have climbed sharply as most investors t=
ook a dim view of Bukele=E2=80=99s experiments with cryptocurrency, warning=
 that the bitcoin bond could push El Salvador further from access to tradit=
ional debt markets and hurt its relationship with the IMF.Sure. Look, if yo=
u want exposure to El Salvador=E2=80=99s credit and Bitcoin, you can spend =
50 cents on El Salvador bonds and 50 cents on Bitcoin and get something tha=
t is so, so much better than a volcano bond. But you don=E2=80=99t want tha=
t. You want to either (1) stay far away from all of this or (2) buy some cr=
ypto financial engineering. You want to buy a Bitcoin-linked sovereign bond=
 because that sounds cool, or because you want to support a country=E2=80=
=99s experiment with Bitcoin as legal currency, or because you want to supp=
ort the development of an ecosystem of crypto-linked bonds. You might want =
that out of, like, naive aesthetic enthusiasm. Or you might be a crypto wha=
le whose net worth is highly levered to the continuing broad adoption of cr=
ypto. You are more or less=C2=A0donating=C2=A0money to El Salvador to make =
this project work, but that might be a positive-value trade for you.Meanwhi=
le if the volcano bond is issued, do you think that the prices will be arbi=
traged? Like will someone buy regular El Salvador bonds plus Bitcoin and sh=
ort the volcano bond until the prices get back in line? No, they absolutely=
 will not; nobody really knows how the volcano bonds will work yet (=E2=80=
=9CImportant details of the bond would need to be ironed out, requiring the=
 passing of new securities laws in El Salvador=E2=80=9D), but I am sure tha=
t it will be unusually painful to sell them short. The volcano bonds will t=
rade among crypto enthusiasts and the regular bonds will trade among emergi=
ng-markets credit enthusiasts and they will never have any interaction with=
 each other.
