   =20
      Virtual interview cheating
   =20
 =20
When I was an investment banker, I would occasionally interview undergradua=
tes looking to get banking jobs. I am trying to imagine what I would have s=
aid if one of them had walked into the room, pulled out a computer, and sai=
d =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sorry, do you mind? I spent 12 hours preparing a hyp=
erlinked document with answers to a range of possible interview=C2=A0questi=
ons, and I=E2=80=99d like to refer to it during our interview. For instance=
, if you were to ask me =E2=80=98what are your strengths and weaknesses,=E2=
=80=99 I=E2=80=99d click into the =E2=80=98Behavioral=E2=80=99 section, the=
n the =E2=80=98Strengths & Weaknesses=E2=80=99 subsection, and I would read=
 off my bullet-pointed list of responses. I think this will make this proce=
ss more efficient and informative for both of us.=E2=80=9DI think I would =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0obviously have hired that person on the spot? That person ha=
s what it takes to be an investment banker! Ooh, so she has to look at her =
notes to do an accretion/dilution model, who cares, you can look at your no=
tes on the job. That=E2=80=99s a person who obsessively prepped for a meeti=
ng! =E2=80=9CObsessively preps for=C2=A0meetings=E2=80=9D is the whole job =
of a junior investment banker! What else could the banks possibly be hiring=
 for if not that?Anyway here is a hilarious Insider story about college stu=
dents who =E2=80=9Ccheated=E2=80=9D in virtual i-banking interviews by spre=
ading hyperlinked notes around their Zoom windows, and now are worried that=
 they won=E2=80=99t be able to =E2=80=9Ccheat=E2=80=9D anymore as interview=
ing is increasingly in-person again:"To be honest, I'm really worried about=
 how I'll do during my interviews now since I won't have access to the mate=
rials I had during COVID," said one Wharton student who asked not to be ide=
ntified in order to openly discuss the use of these answer sheets. "Everybo=
dy's hush-hush about full-time recruiting, but I know it's on everybody's m=
ind." =E2=80=A6The Wharton undergrad who bemoaned the loss of virtual inter=
views admitted to using a Google Doc with notes on behavioral questions whi=
le recruiting for 2022 summer analyst roles last spring. In addition to the=
 Google Doc, the student also relied on 10 pages of handwritten notes that =
addressed technical questions. The handwritten notes were spread out under =
this person's computer.When recruiters asked technical questions about topi=
cs like LBO modeling, the student was able to look down to refer to these p=
apers since recruiters expected that candidates would jot down shorthand no=
tes on scratch paper on their desks in order to perform calculations.Prepar=
ing the notes took almost 12 hours, the student estimated.Another student =
=E2=80=A6 described how she and some of her friends peppered their Google D=
ocs with hyperlinked tables of contents which enabled them, quick as a flas=
h, to jump directly down to the answers to almost any question they were as=
ked.=C2=A0Most students set up their tables of contents using key terms lik=
e "behaviorals," she said, giving users near-instantaneous access to bullet=
ed notes for questions like: "What are your strengths and weaknesses?"=C2=
=A0Honestly why even interview, just have the candidates send the banks Pow=
erPoint decks charting their strengths and weaknesses. The formatting of th=
e PowerPoint deck will be way more informative, for junior banker hiring, t=
han the answers.
