tYm9uZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMzMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc2=
91cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6099e3d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> was</a>:</p><ol style=3D"list-s=
tyle-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Don=E2=80=99t buy El Salvador=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cvolcano=
 bond,=E2=80=9D a 6.5% 10-year dollar bond that also includes a call option=
 on Bitcoins.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Instead, buy El Salv=
ador=E2=80=99s regular 8.25% dollar bond due in 2032 at like 75 cents on th=
e dollar, and use the extra 25 cents to buy Bitcoin.</li></ol><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">I mean, I=E2=80=99m not saying you should do the second tra=
de either, really. I=E2=80=99m just saying that if you find the volcano bon=
d tempting, buying something that <em>is worth more in every scenario=C2=A0=
</em>should be=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>tempting.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Since I wrote that, the 8.25% bonds have traded down to around 50 cen=
ts on the dollar, for a yield of about 20%. Oops? Meanwhile the volcano bon=
ds have not priced yet, but they continue to lurch along, apparently on the=
 previously advertised terms. This makes them a much, much worse deal. But =
they were always a bad deal, so it=E2=80=99s not clear why that would matte=
r. Anyway here=E2=80=99s some more on the volcano bonds, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27201820.262606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQu=
Y29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNGZhNjNjOGMtNTFmNS00NTEyLWI1MjItNzZkZDc1ZTYyOTE2/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB3040b9cd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">from the Financial Times</a>:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">El Salvador=E2=80=99s $1bn bitcoin-backed b=
ond could tap deep wells of capital among cryptocurrency enthusiasts after =
many big international investors have shunned the project.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Demand from bitcoin =E2=80=9Cwhales=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 inve=
stors holding large quantities of the world=E2=80=99s biggest cryptocurrenc=
y =E2=80=94 is likely to be crucial to fundraising for the bond, according =
to people involved with the effort. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 optimism in the crypto community for the offering, which is the first of i=
ts kind from a sovereign borrower, sharply contrasts with most large tradit=
ional investors, who have said they are highly sceptical of the deal.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Buyers of the 10-year bitcoin bond =E2=80=94 whi=
ch offers an annual interest rate of 6.5 per cent along with a share of any=
 upside from the proceeds invested in bitcoin =E2=80=94 would be offering f=
inancing on favourable terms to El Salvador, whose existing 10-year dollar =
bonds currently yield in excess of 20 per cent.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">After a five-year lock-up period El Salvador will sell bitcoin until i=
t recoups its initial investment and then share half of any profit with inv=
estors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those yields have climbed sharply a=
s most investors took a dim view of Bukele=E2=80=99s experiments with crypt=
ocurrency, warning that the bitcoin bond could push El Salvador further fro=
m access to traditional debt markets and hurt its relationship with the IMF=
.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure. Look, if you want expo=
sure to El Salvador=E2=80=99s credit and Bitcoin, you can spend 50 cents on=
 El Salvador bonds and 50 cents on Bitcoin and get something that is so, so=
 much better than a volcano bond. But you don=E2=80=99t want that. You want=
 to either (1) stay far away from all of this or (2) buy some <em>crypto fi=
nancial engineering</em>. You want to buy a Bitcoin-linked sovereign bond b=
ecause that sounds cool, or because you want to support a country=E2=80=99s=
 experiment with Bitcoin as legal currency, or because you want to support =
the development of an ecosystem of crypto-linked bonds. You might want that=
 out of, like, naive aesthetic enthusiasm. Or you might be a crypto whale w=
hose net worth is highly levered to the continuing broad adoption of crypto=
. You are more or less=C2=A0<em>donating=C2=A0</em>money to El Salvador to =
make this project work, but that might be a positive-value trade for you.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if the volcano bond is issued, do =
you think that the prices will be arbitraged? Like will someone buy regular=
 El Salvador bonds plus Bitcoin and short the volcano bond until the prices=
 get back in line? No, they absolutely will not; nobody really knows how th=
e volcano bonds will work yet (=E2=80=9CImportant details of the bond would=
 need to be ironed out, requiring the passing of new securities laws in El =
Salvador=E2=80=9D), but I am sure that it will be unusually painful to sell=
 them short. The volcano bonds will trade among crypto enthusiasts and the =
regular bonds will trade among emerging-markets credit enthusiasts and they=
 will never have any interaction with each other.</p><table class=3D"livein=
